-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Prove that for positive integers m ≤ n the number f(2ᵐ)=4^{2ᵐ}+6^{2ᵐ}+9^{2ᵐ} divides f(2ⁿ)=4^{2ⁿ}+6^{2ⁿ}+9^{2ⁿ}. 2. [Key Idea] Show first that f(x) | f(2x) for every positive integer x; then apply this “doubling” k = n–m times. 3. [Proof] Single, direct proof. Let x be any positive integer and put r = 2^{x}, s = 3^{x}. Then f(x) = 4^{x}+6^{x}+9^{x} = r² + rs + s², f(2x) = 4^{2x}+6^{2x}+9^{2x} = r⁴ + r²s² + s⁴. Factor f(2x): r⁴ + r²s² + s⁴ = (r² + rs + s²)² – 2rs(r² + rs + s²) = (r² + rs + s²) (r² + rs + s² – 2rs). Hence f(2x) = f(x) · (r² + rs + s² – 2rs) so f(x) divides f(2x). Now fix m ≤ n and write n = m + k (k ≥ 0). Repeatedly applying the divisibility just proved, f(2ᵐ) | f(2·2ᵐ) = f(2^{m+1}) | … | f(2^{m+k}) = f(2ⁿ). Therefore f(2ᵐ) divides f(2ⁿ) for all positive integers m ≤ n. 4. [Conclusion] Because f(x) always divides f(2x), each successive doubling preserves divisibility, and thus f(2ᵐ) | f(2ⁿ) whenever m ≤ n.
